Subject: Statistical Analysis using Chi-Square, ANOVA, and Linear Regression Models

Background

In our previous task, we were able to make predictions and conclusions based on our data by using estimates and hypothesis testing to possibly make some generalizations about the Pokemon population. Interestingly, we found through hypothesis testing that the type 1 of a Pokemon did not really have any influence on whether it will have a second type. After conducting different inferential analysis on confidence intervals and hypothesis tests, specializing on parameter, proportion, and mean in our previous data exploration, we are provided with a new task of performing chi-square test of independence, ANOVA, simple linear regression, and multiple linear regression, to analyze the relationships between the variables within our Pokemon dataset. Given this objective, the 5 different analyses will be individually conducted and various visualizations/calculations will be made to test the relationships between each members chosen quantitative and or categorical variables.

Analysis 1: Chi-Square Test of Independence (Generation and Legendary)

Analyst: Jessica Vo

The explanatory variables is Generation and the response variable is Legendary. Since you cannot have more than 4 categories for the variables for a Chi-Square Independence test, I had combined generations 1, 2, and 3 into one category representing the early generations and generations 4, 5, and 6 into one category representing the later generations. I grouped them this way because I wanted to see if being in the early generation or later generation has an effect on whether a Pokemon is legendary.

# Combining categories for the Generation variable into 2 categories (EarlyGen and LateGen)
NewGen <- pokemon_data$Generation
NewGen[NewGen %in% c ("1", "2", "3")] <- "EarlyGen"
NewGen[NewGen %in% c ("4", "5", "6")] <- "LateGen"
NewGen <- as.factor(NewGen)
levels(NewGen)
[1] "EarlyGen" "LateGen" 
# Table representing the 2 variables 
pokemon_matrix <- table(NewGen, pokemon_data$Legendary)
pokemon_matrix
          
NewGen     False True
  EarlyGen   403   29
  LateGen    332   36
# Mosaic Plot of chosen data (visual representation of variables)
mosaicplot(pokemon_matrix)

Conditions:

  1. Independence: This condition is not really met since the sample is not a random sample and consists of pretty much all of the Pokemons from generations 1 to 6.

  2. Sample size: Each cell has at least 5 expected cases, therefore the sample size condition is met.

  3. 2 or more categories for each variable: This condition is met since there are 2 categories for each of the variables chosen.

Null Hypothesis: Pokemon Generation and the Legendary status of Pokemons are independent.

Alternative Hypothesis: Pokemon Generation and the Legendary status of Pokemons are not independent.

chisq.test(pokemon_matrix)

    Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction

data:  pokemon_matrix
X-squared = 2.114, df = 1, p-value = 0.146

Test statistic = 2.114

P-value = 0.146

Conclusion: Since the p-value is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. The data does not provide convincing evidence that Pokemon generation and the legendary status of Pokemons are dependent. It doesnt appear that the legendary status of Pokemons vary by Pokemon generations.

Limitations: One of the conditions for the the Chi-Square Test of Independence was not met. The independence condition was not really met, therefore this is a limitation to the analysis, since not all the conditions werent met, the output might not be as reliable.

The NULL hypothesis is that there is no difference of means between the 4 different Type 1 Pokemon with respect to the Speed statistic. The alternative hypothesis is that the means of the speed of Type 1 Pokemon are not all the same.

## Running the ANOVA test
aov.all <- aov(pokemon_common$Speed ~ pokemon_common$Type.1, data = pokemon_common)
summary (aov.all)

The test statistic (F-value) is 2.342 and the P-value is 0.073. These values lead me to accept the NULL hypothesis of there being no significant difference in the mean Speed value of the 4 most common Pokemon Types. This means that the most populated Type 1 categories do not have very different mean speed statistics. Calculating the power of this ANOVA test results in a power value of 0.89, which says that this test is a good and valid test to use.

Since all of the ANOVA conditions were met there are no limitations from that side of things, so we are able to use this test. Since the response variable is something like Speed of the Pokemon that means that there wont be any outliers that need to be removed since there wont be any extreme values like 0.

Analyst: Elaine Tse

In my simple linear regression analysis, the two quantitative variables I examined are Pokemon HP (Health) and SpAtk (Special Attack). The explanatory variable is SpAtk and the response variable is HP. Within the pokemon dataset, there werent any NA values to be removed in relation to the two variables I am working with, thus no data cleaning was necessary.

In the context of my analysis, my null and alternative hypothesis is:

Null Hypothesis: There is no association between Pokemon HP (Health) and Pokemon SpAtk (Special Attack)

Alternative Hypothesis: There is an association between Pokemon HP (Health) and Pokemon SpAtk (Special Attack)

The Linear Regression line of my data is: HP = 48.66662 + 0.28278SpAtk

As for the summary of the linear regression model I created, I am given the slope and intercept:

Slope = 0.28278

Intercept = 48.66662

As for the test statistics and p-value of my data, the summary statistic of the linear regression model also provided me with its values. The t-statistic for SpAtk is 10.98 and the t-statistic for the intercept is 23.68. The p-value is the same for both t-statistics, which is 2e-16 (very close to 0). Due to both t-statistics being large and the p-value being extremely small, it indicates a statistically significant coefficient. This also tells us that there is an association between the explanatory variable, SpAtk (x), and the response variable, HP (y). With that said, I can reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternative hypothesis (that there is a significant association between SpAtk and HP).

For this analysis, we must address the 4 conditions that need to be met for linear regression: Linearity, Homoscedasticity, Independence, Normality

To start off, I first created a linear regression model and examined its summary of statistics. There I was provided the residuals, coefficients, slope, intercept, standard errors, t values, p-value for t-test, significance codes, residual standard error, and r-squared. With this information, I created a residuals vs fitted plot to examine the linearity of the data. In the plot, there is a somewhat distributed scatter. With that in mind, there also wasnt any noticeable pronounced pattern so we can assume that there is an indication for a linear relationship. Some clumping can also be seen on the left side of the residuals vs fitted plot, but we can assume that the linear assumption is met.

For the Homoscedasticity condition, I created a spread-location plot that examines if the residuals are equally spread amongst the ranges of predictors. In the plot, there is a spread of points but it can be seen that the variability of residual points are slightly increasing and then decreasing with the fitted values. The horizontal line appears to zig-zag near the middle of the graph, but still maintains its horizontal directions where the y-axis is 0.8 or 0.9. With that said, the graph doesnt display any extreme variability issues (graph representing certain shapes), therefore we can assume the condition is met (also due to the horizontal line having a somewhat equal spread of points).

For the Independence condition, looking back on the residuals versus fits scatter plot, there was a somewhat distributed scatter of points. We can assume that the residuals are independent because the graph doesnt appear like there is a relationship or pattern of some sort.

Lastly, for the Normality condition, I created a Normal Q-Q plot and histogram plot to check the normality of residuals. In the Normal Q-Q plot, most of the points fall close to the line, however there is a slight curving at the end heading upwards. The points at the start of the line, where the theoretical quantities are -3 and 3, slightly stand out from the rest of the data points in the middle. As for the histogram plot, the residuals appear to be slightly right skewed, thus indicating it isnt normally distributed. With this information, we can assume that all conditions are valid except for normality.

In terms of the goodness of fit for the linear regression model, the R-squared value is 0.1313192. The regression model consists of a low R-squared value (13.1% out of 100%). Essentially, this means that the model lacks thorough explanation of the variation in the response variable (HP) around its mean and that the scatter of the data points around the fitted regression line has a somewhat large difference between the observed data and fitted values.

Furthermore, there are a couple limitations that need to be addressed. Due to the linear regression line not meeting all of the conditions (unable to meet normality), this is a limitation that suggests for me to transform the data or find a more appropriate distribution with different variables. There are also noticeable extreme points (262, 218, and 122) and outliers within the data after plotting a residuals vs leverage plot. A couple outliers fall on the right side of the graph, thus making the data skewed to the right and most likely affecting the slope of the regression line.

Overall, the two quantitative variables I analyzed, HP being the response variable and SpAtk being the explanatory variable, can be assumed that there is an association. Various plots and diagnostics were used to determine whether or not the linear regression of HP and SpAtk have met the linear model conditions. After the conditions were examined, I was able to determine the null and alternative hypotheses, analyze further on the statistics of the regression, specifically t-values and p-values, and conclude on an associating relationship between Pokemon HP and SpAtk.

We are trying to observe a linear relationship between these two variables and HP. Several conditions must be met for our multiple linear regression model to be usable, linearity (each variable being linearly related to the outcome), independence of residuals, residuals that are nearly normal, and equal variability among residuals. By observing our correlation matrix, we can see that the two explanatory variables that we have chosen come close but still do not seem to have a linear relationship with our response variable, violating our first condition. Our third condition of normality of residuals is clearly violated when observing the upper right portion of the QQ plot. Our fourth condition of constant variance appears to be violated as well, which we can see in the graph which plots our residuals against our predicted values.

For our data, we will state our null hypothesis as there being no linear relationship between the response variable of HP and the two quantitative variables of Attack and SpDef. Our alternative hypothesis being that there exists some linear relationship between the two explanatory variables of Attack and SpDef and our response variable of HP.

After obtaining our regression model, we can see that the test statistic for our Attack coefficient is 10.934 with a p-value <2e-16. Our test statistic for the SpDef coefficient is 9.062 while our p-value is <2e-16. Seeing that both of our coefficients are demonstrating extreme statistical significance it would be sensible to reject our null hypothesis. However, it is important to note that this model has an adjusted R-squared of .2533, meaning that approximately 25% of the variation in our response variable can be explained by our explanatory variables. All being said, this model has its limitations and should not be used as a predictive model. It failed to meet nearly all of the conditions, by referring to the outlier test ran in R, there are a few observable outliers in our data, and it also has a demonstrated adjusted R-squared that is well outside of an acceptable range.

Recommendations

Through the chi-square test of independence, we found that there is not enough evidence to say that the legendary status of Pokemons depend on what generation they are in. Some limitations to the findings was that 2 of the conditions for the test were not met, so this could make the results not as reliable and maybe inaccurate. This gives us insight on how generation is probably not a criteria when determining whether a Pokemon is given legendary status or not.

Upon constructing a linear multiple regression model with HP as our response variable and Attack/SpDef as our explanatory variables, it became apparent that these two explanatory variables are extremely statistically significant (highly unlikely to be due to chance) in terms of being valid predictors of our response variable. However, the model which included these predictors violated several of the necessary conditions for our model to be considered a good predictive method. Only a small (~25%) amount of the variation in our response variable could be explained by our explanatory variables. This offers us new insight into observing a possible linear relationship between Attack/SpDef and HP, but there needs to be work done, perhaps via transformation of the regression, to have a model that can be effectively used as a predictor of total HP.

By conducting an analysis of variance test on the Speed of the four main Type 1 Pokemon we can understand if there is a relationship between the two. The results of the ANOVA test show that there is not a statistically significant difference between the mean speed of the main Type 1 Pokemon, meaning the most populated Type 1 categories do not have very different mean speed statistics. A limitation in this finding is that it only relates four main types of Pokemon, and there might be a statistical difference in speed in other types of Pokemon. It doesnt necessarily show any groundbreaking patterns in the data since speed seems to be a value that exists in a pretty small range, meaning there are no extreme values.

After creating a linear regression model with SpAtk as the explanatory model and HP as the response variable, I was able to determine that the statistics for my variables (SpAtk and HP) are significant in relation to determining an association between the predictor (SpAtk) and the outcome variables (HP). Although the linear regression model failed to meet the normality condition, the predictor and response variable was able to show valid results (meeting the conditions) for Homoscedasticity, Independence, and Linearity. In my findings, I came across a couple of limitations, which are the outliers from the regression line (based on HP and SpAtk) and the unmet normality condition for the linear regression model. With that said, this provides us a new insight in using different variables that are better matched for the linear model conditions or using non-linear transformations of the predictors in the regression model (log, square root, etc) to avoid possible fitted patterns in linearity and homogeneity of variance.
